Modern email clients (Outlook, Gmail) automatically process meeting requests embedded within emails — no user interaction required to add them to the calendar. This behavior, designed for productivity , creates an exploitable attack surface.

The problem exists because calendar applications process and display event information without properly checking or cleaning the data. This allows an attacker to:
Inject meeting events directly into a victim's calendar
Spoof the identity of the apparent organizer
Embed malicious URLs disguised as legitimate conferencing links
Silently modify or cancel existing meetings

Modern clients automatically process meeting invitations using standardized protocols
iCalendar (RFC 5545) – Defines calendar event format.
iTIP (RFC 5546) – Defines scheduling operations (request, cancel, update).
iMIP (RFC 6047) – Defines how scheduling messages are transported over email.

Why It Matters:
The attack bypasses conventional phishing detection because no malicious attachment or link is required in the email body itself
Events persist in the calendar even after the originating email is deleted
It enables both initial access (credential harvesting from external targets) and lateral movement (internal phishing from a compromised account)
Notifications propagate to integrated tools like Microsoft Teams, expanding the attack surface.


Anatomy of a VCALENDAR / VEVENT Object:

In iCalendar messages, VCALENDAR is the main container that holds event components. VEVENT represents a single calendar event (meeting, appointment, or reminder) and appears between BEGIN:VEVENT and END:VEVENT.

Each event includes several properties that describe it. While clients may interpret some fields differently, a few properties are required for the event to function properly.

SUMMARY:
The meeting title. This is usually the name that appears in calendar views.

DESCRIPTION:
The detailed text of the meeting, such as notes or instructions.

LOCATION:
The physical location or virtual meeting link (e.g., Zoom or Teams URL).

SEQUENCE:
A version number for the event. Each time the organizer updates the meeting, this number increases so calendar clients know it replaces an older version.

STATUS:
Indicates the meeting state:

TENTATIVE

CONFIRMED

CANCELLED

CLASS:
Defines the privacy level of the event:

PUBLIC
PRIVATE
CONFIDENTIAL

RRULE:
Defines recurrence rules for repeating meetings (optional), such as daily or weekly events.




